Course.create(title: 'BMEG 4213.  Cell and Tissue Mechanics  (Irregular).  3 Hours.', description: 'The purpose of this course is to introduce students to biomechanics at different length scales. Topics covered: Tissue mechanics: continuum biomechanics, tensor analysis, kinematics of continua, balance laws. Governing physics of mechanics as applied to soft tissues. Constitutive relations for tissues: linear elastic, hyperelastic, viscoelastic, poroelastic. Cell mechanics: Intro to cell biology and biochemistry. Influence of load, pressure, stress, strain on cell shape and integrity. Measuring cell and tissue properties experimentally. Energy and entropy for different cellular units: biopolymers (microtubules, actin, intermediate filaments, biomembranes). Mechanotransduction of load through cell and matrix. Cannot receive credit for both BMEG 4213 and BMEG 5213. Pre- or', coreqDesc: 'BMEG 4623.', coreqData: '{ "Course0": [{ "name":"BMEG 4623","grade":"D" }]}', prereqDesc: ':  BMEG 2813, BMEG Major and Senior standing.', prereqData: '{ "Course0": [{ "name":"BMEG 2813","grade":"D" }],"Course1": [{ "name":"SENIOR"}]}')
Course.create(title: 'BMEG 4243.  Advanced Biomaterials and Biocompatibility  (Sp).  3 Hours.', description: 'From Absorbable sutures to Zirconium alloy hip implants, biomaterials science influences nearly every aspect of medicine. This course focuses on the study of different classes of biomaterials and their interactions with human tissues. Topics include: biocompatibility; biofouling; hemocompatibility; wound healing response; foreign body response; design of orthopedic, dental and cardiovascular implants; opthalmological and dermatological materials; degradable polymers for drug delivery; nanobiomaterials; smart biomaterials and the regulation of devices and materials by the FDA.  Pre- or', coreqDesc: 'BMEG 4623.', coreqData: '{ "Course0": [{ "name":"BMEG 4623","grade":"D" }]}', prereqDesc: ':  BMEG 3634.', prereqData: '{ "Course0": [{ "name":"BMEG 3634","grade":"D" }]}')
